EAS iOS Build Guide for Client

Step-by-Step Guide: Building Your iOS App with Expo EAS

1. Install Node.js
- Go to: https://nodejs.org/
- Click the big green "LTS" button to download.
- Open the downloaded file and follow the instructions to install.

2. Install Expo and EAS Tools
- Open the Command Prompt (search for "cmd" in the Start menu).
- Copy and paste this command, then press Enter:
  npm install -g expo-cli eas-cli
- Wait for it to finish (it may take a few minutes).

3. Get the Project Files
- Download the project folder (your developer will send you a ZIP file or a link).
- Unzip the folder to your Desktop or another easy-to-find location.

4. Open the Project Folder in Command Prompt
- In Command Prompt, type cd  (with a space after it).
- Drag and drop the unzipped project folder into the Command Prompt window.
- Press Enter. (This changes the directory to your project folder.)

5. Install Project Dependencies
- In the same Command Prompt window, type:
  npm install
- Press Enter and wait for it to finish (this may take a few minutes).

6. Log in to Expo
- In Command Prompt, type:
  eas login
- Press Enter.
- When prompted, enter your Expo account email and password.
  - If you don't have an Expo account, go to https://expo.dev/signup and create one.

7. Start the iOS Build
- In Command Prompt, type:
  eas build --profile production --platform ios
- Press Enter.
- When asked, log in with your Apple Developer account (this is required by Apple for security).

8. Wait for the Build to Finish
- The process will take a few minutes.
- When it's done, you'll get a link to download your iOS app file.

9. Download and Test Your App
- Click the link provided in the Command Prompt to download your app.
- You can now test it or upload it to the App Store.

TROUBLESHOOTING & SUPPORT
- If you get stuck, copy any error messages and send them to your developer for help.
- Don't close the Command Prompt window until the process is finished.
- For more help, visit https://docs.expo.dev/build/introduction/ or contact your developer.

Good luck! You can do it! 